---
/**
 * Focused 6-row comparison table for the Calcarenite entry.
 * Clean, maritime, not too rigid – subtle borders, good typography, layman-friendly notes.
 * Styled to sit nicely inside the reading surface as a distinct "boxed" element per the sketch.
 */
---

<div class="comparison-table not-prose my-8 rounded-xl border border-black/10 bg-white/65 p-4 shadow-sm md:p-5">
  <div class="mb-3 text-[12px] font-medium uppercase tracking-[0.75px] text-[#5c6b7a]">
    Scientific comparison
  </div>

  <table class="w-full border-collapse text-[13.5px] leading-relaxed">
    <thead>
      <tr class="border-b border-black/10 text-left text-[#2c2c2c]">
        <th class="py-2 pr-3 font-semibold">Property</th>
        <th class="py-2 pr-3 font-semibold">Calcarenite<br><span class="text-[11px] font-normal text-[#5c6b7a]">(Athalassa, S. Cyprus)</span></th>
        <th class="py-2 pr-3 font-semibold">Chalk<br><span class="text-[11px] font-normal text-[#5c6b7a]">(e.g. Lefkara Fm.)</span></th>
        <th class="py-2 font-semibold">Reef / Hard Limestone<br><span class="text-[11px] font-normal text-[#5c6b7a]">(typical)</span></th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody class="text-[#333]">
      <tr class="border-b border-black/5">
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3 font-medium text-[#1f1f1f]">Texture / Grain size</td>
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3">Sand-sized (0.06–2 mm) carbonate grains, often cross-bedded. Feels gritty, like a sandstone made of shells.</td>
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3">Extremely fine (mostly &lt;0.06 mm nannofossils &amp; micrite). Smooth, almost powdery when weathered.</td>
        <td class="py-2.5">Larger framework fossils bound together. More massive and “stony” to the touch.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="border-b border-black/5">
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3 font-medium text-[#1f1f1f]">Composition &amp; Porosity</td>
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3">Mostly calcite from bioclasts (foraminifera, shells, algae). High porosity (often 15–30%+) – water and salts move easily.</td>
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3">Almost pure fine calcite. Very high porosity but tiny pores; more uniform and “chalky”.</td>
        <td class="py-2.5">Calcite framework + cement. Lower porosity, denser fabric.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="border-b border-black/5">
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3 font-medium text-[#1f1f1f]">Hardness &amp; Durability</td>
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3">Relatively soft and friable (Mohs ~3). Can be cut or break along grain boundaries. Historically used as building stone because it is workable.</td>
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3">Very soft. Scratches easily with a fingernail or knife. Weathers by powdering or dissolution rather than flaking.</td>
        <td class="py-2.5">Harder and more resistant due to cementation and bound structure. Often used for more durable construction.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="border-b border-black/5">
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3 font-medium text-[#1f1f1f]">Age &amp; Environment (Cyprus)</td>
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3">Pliocene (~5–2.5 Ma, some ~4 Ma exposures). Shallow, high-energy marine seaway between rising Troodos and Kyrenia landmasses. Cross-bedded sands.</td>
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3">Much older (Paleogene, ~50+ Ma). Deep, quiet pelagic seas – fine ooze raining down from the water column.</td>
        <td class="py-2.5">Variable, often Miocene or older reef build-ups. Warm, shallow, clear waters where organisms grew in place.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr class="border-b border-black/5">
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3 font-medium text-[#1f1f1f]">Response to Haloclasty (salt weathering)</td>
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3">Highly susceptible. Sea spray soaks the open pores; salt crystals grow and pry grains apart. Produces classic tafoni (honeycomb holes) and granular sand on the south coast.</td>
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3">Less dramatic granular breakdown. Tends to soften and powder or develop solution features rather than deep caverns.</td>
        <td class="py-2.5">Much more resistant. Lower porosity and stronger cement mean slower physical breakdown even in spray zones.</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3 font-medium text-[#1f1f1f]">Cyprus Uses &amp; Context</td>
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3">Important historical building stone (Athalassa / “Nicosia calcarenite”). Today valued for the sculptural tafoni it develops and as a record of Cyprus’s emergence from the sea.</td>
        <td class="py-2.5 pr-3">Widely used for carved detail in older architecture (softer to work). Forms the pale “backbone” hills of the island.</td>
        <td class="py-2.5">Often more massive blocks or decorative stone. More resistant outcrops and different fossil assemblages.</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p class="mt-3 text-[12px] text-[#666]">
    All three are limestones (mostly CaCO<sub>3</sub>), but their grain size, porosity, and cementation control how they look, feel, and weather along the Cypriot coast.
  </p>
</div>